Bridgeburners	The Bridgeburners were a legendary elite division in the Malazan 2nd Army who were respected by the majority of the Malazan Empire and even their enemies. The unit symbol was a stone arched bridge, lit with ruby flames.<br><br> <i>"First in, last out." (Motto of the Bridgeburners)</i><br><br> <i>"A Bridgeburner—such a strange name for soldiers, and yet . . . so perfect there in the chasm between the living and the dead." (Kalyth)</i>
Bucklund	A Bridgeburner soldier marked by his dry wit and stubborn resilience, one of the many hardened veterans shaped by years of imperial wars.<br>
Cage	A member of the Bridgeburners recorded in the rolls of the unit, with only fragmentary notes on his actions in the field.<br>
Corinn	A Bridgeburner whose presence is briefly recorded among the squad’s soldiers, with little surviving detail beyond her service.<br>
Dasalle	A Bridgeburner trooper appearing in the chronicles as part of the legendary unit’s strength, though few specifics of her life are given.<br>
Detoran	A tough, no-nonsense Bridgeburner sergeant known for her iron discipline and readiness to stand shoulder to shoulder with her troops.<br>
Ferret	A Bridgeburner whose name appears among the squad’s ranks, representing the many ordinary soldiers who fought and died with little fanfare.<br>
Fiddler	Sapper of the 9th Squad, Bridgeburners, serving alongside Hedge under Sergeant Whiskeyjack; born in Malaz City but of Falari descent. A wiry man with bandied legs, lank red hair and beard, massive wrists, and pale blue eyes, his hands and face bore pockmarks from explosive detonations. He carried a broken, scorched fiddle strapped to his back — hence his name. Possessed a rare natural Talent recognized by High Mage Tattersail: he often had "bad feelings" that forewarned him and others of impending danger, saving lives during the Siege of Pale. An adept at reading the Deck of Dragons, he used it for divination and card games, creating new rules each time he dealt to guarantee his winning.<br>
Ganoes Stabro Paran|Ganoes|Paran	A noble-born Malazan officer, eldest son of House Paran of Unta, who became closely tied to the Bridgeburners and later served as Master of the Deck, his fate intertwined with the unit’s legacy. Paran was described as having black hair, an easy face to rest eyes upon and a broad back. He wore a helm as part of his uniform and when on the road, wore a travelling cloak.<br>
Gent	A lesser-known Bridgeburner whose recorded presence underlines the breadth of the unit, though few personal details remain in the chronicles.<br>
Hedge	Fiddler’s fellow sapper, reckless and bold with Moranth munitions, whose courage and wild gambling spirit became legendary among the Bridgeburners.<br>
Kalam Mekhar|Kalam	A former Claw assassin from the Seven Cities, later turned Bridgeburner. Black-skinned and described as moving effortlessly despite his girth, he wore mocassins and spoke with a north Seven Cities accent, melodic and round. Kalam's favourite weapon was the compact crossbow used by the Claw, sometimes carrying a pair of them attached to wrist braces under his voluminous sleeves.<br><br><i>"A damned legend, the finest killer the Claw ever had--and lost." (Pearl)</i><br>
Liss	A Bridgeburner associated with the unit’s later history, her recorded role limited but emblematic of the many soldiers drawn into its ranks.<br>
Mallet	The squad’s healer and a priest of Fener, a calm and steady presence who kept the Bridgeburners alive through countless wounds and disasters.<br>
Monkrat	A Bridgeburner whose name survives among the unit’s lists, with little more than hints of his service during the Genabackan campaigns.<br>
Mulch	A trooper of the Bridgeburners noted in passing by the chroniclers, representing the many unsung soldiers of the Malazan wars.<br>
Pahvral	A lesser-detailed Bridgeburner whose membership in the unit is noted, though few specific deeds are recorded in the main histories.<br>
Picker	A sharp-tongued veteran who later commanded the surviving Bridgeburners in Darujhistan, balancing ruthlessness with responsibility for her people.<br>
Ben Adaephon Delat|Quick Ben|Delat	Mage of the 9th Squad, Bridgeburners, originally from the Seven Cities continent. Black-skinned and tall with a lean face and fine ascetic features, he had a row of neat, smallish, white teeth. His arms were scrawny, and his long hands were almost feminine and also described as thin and spidery. He wore leather armour over a heavy quilted tunic, thin wool undergarments, leather leggings, and moccasins. His voice took on a strange lilt whenever he struggled against speaking his mind. He had a habit of licking his lips when nervous.<br><br> Whiskeyjack once stated that while Kruppe might have been the most intelligent man alive, Quick Ben was but a short step behind.<br>
Rayez	A Bridgeburner soldier with only sparse references in the chronicles, one of many who fought within the shadow of more famous comrades.<br>
Runter	A Bridgeburner trooper whose recorded role is limited, standing for the countless ordinary soldiers that made the unit’s reputation possible.<br>
